# Introduction. What is Oman? {#introduction.-what-is-oman?}

As a very high overview Oman is a Marketing Tool. It is intended to handle the whole process for marketers from doing initial prospect research to sending a campaign to those that could potentially become a deal.

This would be a normal user flow: 

1. Register / Login in the App  
2. Create a new Campaign  
3. Add the Linkedin Link / Sales Navigation Link (Depending the Campaign Setup)  
4. Linked In Prospects / Leads Crawling  
5. Email Finder (using Dropcontact.io or Hunter.io apis)  
6. AI Categorization  
7. Automatic description with OpenAI   
8. Send it to email Marketing Campaign  (ZOHO Campaigns)

A logged user can generate N campaigns. Each campaign is intended to wrap all the prospect logic. 

This Main Project (Oman) Splits in different Projects and we are focusing on this document in the Oman App Project. 

# Oman APP {#oman-app}

The Oman App is responsible for encapsulating all the business logic to provide the service to the final user. It is split into two subprojects. “Oman Server App” that exposes a Rest API for consumption And “Oman Client App” that builds a Web App based on standard web technologies.

Important: 

Oman Server App is not responsible itself of: 

- Crawl Linkedin  
- Find and verify Emails  
- AI Categorization  
- Send Campaigns

All these operations are handled by other projects not described in this document. 

Oman Server App has a data model where the state (creation / update / delete) of those operations is handled by other services / projects asynchronously.

Data Model acts as a source of truth between all the services forming Oman.

# Oman App Modules {#oman-app-modules}

As any other Web App Oman App (OA) it’s split in different modules very related to the UI/UX needs.

- Authentication   
- Campaign Management   
- Lead Management  
- Settings

## Authentication  {#authentication}

This module follows the well known best practices for sign up and sign in. 

The sign up will contain a form with FirstName, LastName, Email and Password. Also will allow third party sign up using Providers like Google and Apple.

All fields will be mandatory. 

After Sign up is satisfied an intermediary step will prompt him to go to his inbox and confirm an email. 

Once it is done access to the dashboard will be allowed. Not before. Confirm the email is mandatory

The sign in page will be a form where user will be able to sign using either the email / password or using a third party provider 

In this iteration we don’t evaluate having roles so authorization is simplified.

If a user does not remember his password always will be able to request a new password by clicking on a link in the sign in page. 

This link will bring him to a new form where he can add his email.

### Technical Add ons {#technical-add-ons}

The third party login and the email login will have to be synced. It means that if a user signs up using his email, later on logs in using a third party provider and then we find out it is the same email than the one he signed up for, both data will be merged and synced in the database.

Validation happens on both sides, backend and frontend. As backend exposes a Rest API consumed by the Frontend it is important how Backend and Frontend communicate: They will communicate using JSON object when answer is a 200 and for errors always will return HTTP error number following best API practices.

For sending the emails we will rely on Zoho Zepto transaction platform. 

For confirming the email we will use websocket technology. It means the following, register is done and email is sent. A temporary screen / popup appears prompting the user to go to the inbox. The application internally opens a websocket with the server and waits for email to be confirmed.   
User goes to his inbox, clicks the email and, once the request is sent to the server, the server using websocket notifies the client.

## Campaigns Managment {#campaigns-managment}

It is a CRUD Module where the user can manage the campaigns

A campaign has the following information to be edited / updated

- Campaign Name  
- Email Subject: The subject of the email will be send to our leads (English)  
- Email Body: the Body the email will be send out leads (English)  
- Crawling Status: When the crawling is rolled out. Status can be on queue, processing, finished  
- Type Campaign: Linkedin or Sales Navigator  
- Search Url: The Linkeidn SN url that the crawl uses to crawl for leads

A given user can have multiple campaigns managing and running in parallel.

In the Campaign Form besides to add / update the Campaign data you can also crawl & enrich the data through a button. This button will be only enabled when the crawl URL is in place. 

Also you have a **“Delete button”** to delete the campaign (is a soft delete, campaign is not deleted from the DB).

If the campaign finishes, a **button** to send the campaign will allow it to send the campaign. This button will be disabled if crown is not finished

Also we will have an **input text and a button named “Send as Te**st”. If this button is pressed all the leads emails will be sent to the email filled in the “input text field”. This button is disabled also if crawl is not finished. 

- 

In the Campaign List Page you have besides the list of the campaigns paginated as shown in this screenshot 2 buttons: 

“Edit button” to edit the campaign with a form following the instructions given before.

A “See Leads” button to see the related leads to the Campaign

And the following information as a paginated list: 

- Name of the campaign  
- Status Crawling / Enrichment  
- Type of Campaign  
- Status of the Campaign, it was already sent (the emails)  
- Number of emails found / leads

## Leads Management {#leads-management}

When a campaign finishes to crawl (remember, with another process external from the Oman App) the output is stored in Leads Entity.

For a Given Campaign you can query for the leads retrieved. 

For each Lead we have

- First Name  
- Last Name  
- Email  
- Company  
- Company Description

Of course each lead is associated with a given campaign. 1 Campaign \- N Leads

Lead Data can be edited and removed like any other CRUD entity, this time directly in the list view and you can add a new one to the list

If the campaign crawl is again triggered the existing leads are removed and replaced for the new ones. A Popup should inform first of the destructiveness of the step allowing the user to cancel.

When leads are removed, they are physically removed, but there is a status flag set to “deleted” so they are invisible but they can be found in the database.

Leads should have also updated\_at and created\_at that tell us when the crawl process was finished. (Because once it happens, it will be in that moment that the leads will be bulked as batch in the table)

![][image2]

## Settings {#settings}

In settings we configure all the needed parameters to run successfully our crawling. This includes: 

- Linkedin cookie: it is an string the crawl service will need for crawling Linkedin  
- DropContact API Key: we use dropcontact for enrich our emails with a service (not part of this Oman App Project)  
- Zoho Campaigns API key for configuring   
- Email Bounce Address  
- Email Domain  
- Email Sender

This is a Form where the user can add / edit  the settings. All of them are mandatory and are the very first step to configure to use the app

If this data is not fulfilled “campaigns pages” or “lead pages” will show a popup that will disallow to use them.

# Technical Architecture  {#technical-architecture}

Oman is split into 3 different services, as described this document takes care only of the API, the Web and the database that act as source of truth. 

- A Backend API to interact with different clients  (Web / Mobile App / Desktop App)  
- A Frontend (Web / Mobile App / Desktop App)   
- The Database

![][image4]

Each module will live in its own microservice, docker kubernetes based. This is both valid for FE and BE

- Authentication Frontend Microservice / Authentication Backend Microservice (API)  
- Campaign Frontend Microservice / Campaign Backend Microservice (API)  
- Lead tool Frontend Microservice / Prospection tool Backend Microservice (API)  
- Settings Frontend Microservice / Settings tool Backend Microservice (API)  
- Shared postgres@16 DB 

Front End Design has to be responsive, clean and elegant and using Typescript with React 19 and Material UI 6.1.1

Backend Rest API Design has to be solid, using OpenaAPI 3.1 specification built in Java and Spring Boot 3.3.4

Implement a log system so we know when users have logged in, which actions they have triggered 

## Database Model

For Postgres 16\. Pending to be AI generated.
